<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="210" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1075,813,1660]" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">
REMARKS: 
<taxonomicName box="[344,536,1050,1073]" class="Arachnida" family="Hersiliidae" genus="Hersilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="210" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sundaica">
<emphasis box="[344,536,1050,1073]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Hersilia sundaica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[706,849,1050,1073]" pageId="3" pageNumber="210" rank="species" species="impressifrons">
<emphasis box="[706,849,1050,1073]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">impressifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group which can be easily recognized by the peculiar structure of the male palp: the TA is complicated, provided with: 1) a membranous apical flange with serrated margin (
<figureCitation box="[875,942,1114,1137]" captionStart="FIGS 6-10" captionStartId="4.[551,593,1187,1208]" captionTargetBox="[159,1030,232,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1039,228,1173]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGS 6-10 Hersilia sundaica. (6) Left male palp, prolateral view. (7) Ditto, ventral view. (8) Ditto, retrolateral view. (9) Epigyne, ventral view. (10) Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305437/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
, AF), and a bifurcated apical prong directed postero-retrolaterad (Fig. 8, AP); 2) lateral process of TA (lP) a large sclerotized, C-shaped plate, partially membranous, retrolaterally with a spoon-shaped projection (
<figureCitation box="[438,536,1210,1233]" captionStart="FIGS 6-10" captionStartId="4.[551,593,1187,1208]" captionTargetBox="[159,1030,232,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1039,228,1173]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGS 6-10 Hersilia sundaica. (6) Left male palp, prolateral view. (7) Ditto, ventral view. (8) Ditto, retrolateral view. (9) Epigyne, ventral view. (10) Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305437/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Figs 6-8</figureCitation>
, lPr), anteriorly with a median tubercle clearly visible in retrolateral view (Fig. 8, lPt), a membranous flange (
<figureCitation box="[839,933,1242,1265]" captionStart="FIGS 6-10" captionStartId="4.[551,593,1187,1208]" captionTargetBox="[159,1030,232,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1039,228,1173]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGS 6-10 Hersilia sundaica. (6) Left male palp, prolateral view. (7) Ditto, ventral view. (8) Ditto, retrolateral view. (9) Epigyne, ventral view. (10) Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305437/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Figs 7-8</figureCitation>
, lPf), and an elongated prong directed posteriad, its apex bifurcated (
<figureCitation box="[745,809,1274,1297]" captionStart="FIGS 6-10" captionStartId="4.[551,593,1187,1208]" captionTargetBox="[159,1030,232,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1039,228,1173]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGS 6-10 Hersilia sundaica. (6) Left male palp, prolateral view. (7) Ditto, ventral view. (8) Ditto, retrolateral view. (9) Epigyne, ventral view. (10) Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305437/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, lPp); 3) median process of TA (mP) with two large prongs, a basal prong abruptly bent, obliquely directed anteriad (
<figureCitation box="[229,297,1338,1361]" captionStart="FIGS 6-10" captionStartId="4.[551,593,1187,1208]" captionTargetBox="[159,1030,232,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1039,228,1173]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGS 6-10 Hersilia sundaica. (6) Left male palp, prolateral view. (7) Ditto, ventral view. (8) Ditto, retrolateral view. (9) Epigyne, ventral view. (10) Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305437/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, mPb), apical prong elongated, its apex membranous, fan-like (
<figureCitation box="[1001,1068,1338,1361]" captionStart="FIGS 6-10" captionStartId="4.[551,593,1187,1208]" captionTargetBox="[159,1030,232,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1039,228,1173]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGS 6-10 Hersilia sundaica. (6) Left male palp, prolateral view. (7) Ditto, ventral view. (8) Ditto, retrolateral view. (9) Epigyne, ventral view. (10) Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305437/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, mPa). Females are recognized by the protruded epigyne extending posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[995,1060,1370,1393]" captionStart="FIGS 6-10" captionStartId="4.[551,593,1187,1208]" captionTargetBox="[159,1030,232,1170]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[153,1039,228,1173]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGS 6-10 Hersilia sundaica. (6) Left male palp, prolateral view. (7) Ditto, ventral view. (8) Ditto, retrolateral view. (9) Epigyne, ventral view. (10) Vulva, dorsal view. Scale lines = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305437/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), copulatory orifices situated close to excavated posterior margin; vulva (Figs 10, 28) provided with parallel insemination ducts running mid-longitudinally, ascending anteriorly then curving laterally to form large glandular apparatus (
<figureCitation box="[848,931,1466,1489]" captionStart="FIGS 27-31" captionStartId="12.[550,592,1407,1428]" captionTargetBox="[136,1058,729,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[136,1058,729,1366]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGS 27-31 Hersilia asiatica (27), H. sundaica (28, 31), H. cf. striata (29), H. serrata sp. n., paratype (30). (27-28) Vulva, dorsal view. (29-30) Right half of vulva, dorsal view. (31) Seminal receptacle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305460/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
); two pilose, spherical receptacula (
<figureCitation box="[394,473,1498,1521]" captionStart="FIGS 27-31" captionStartId="12.[550,592,1407,1428]" captionTargetBox="[136,1058,729,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[136,1058,729,1366]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGS 27-31 Hersilia asiatica (27), H. sundaica (28, 31), H. cf. striata (29), H. serrata sp. n., paratype (30). (27-28) Vulva, dorsal view. (29-30) Right half of vulva, dorsal view. (31) Seminal receptacle." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/305460/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
) with short stalks situated anteriorly. The females examined lack a glandular patch which is present in the female 
<typeStatus box="[799,891,1530,1553]" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">paratype</typeStatus>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[958,1065,1530,1553]" name="Indonesia" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="210" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1075,813,1660]" pageId="3" pageNumber="210">NATURAL HISTORY: All specimens examined were collected by means of a Malaise trap suggesting that this species is rather active and does not stay on the same tree as previous observations made us believe.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
